      chapters: '11–27',
      summary: `Thornfield Hall is the longest and most dramatically charged section of the novel. Jane arrives as governess to Adèle Varens, the young ward of Edward Rochester, and is welcomed by the kindly housekeeper Mrs Fairfax. Thornfield is a grand but somewhat gloomy mansion, and Jane soon becomes aware of mysterious occurrences: strange laughter from the third storey, unexplained noises, and an air of secrecy. She is told that the laughter belongs to Grace Poole, a servant. Jane meets Rochester when his horse slips on ice and he is thrown; she helps him without knowing his identity. Their relationship develops through a series of intense, intellectually charged conversations in which Rochester treats Jane as an equal — a novelty for both of them. Rochester is brooding, mercurial, and burdened by a secret past, and Jane is drawn to him despite (or because of) his complexity.

The Thornfield section contains several Gothic set-pieces: someone sets fire to Rochester's bed while he sleeps, and Jane saves his life; the mysterious figure of Bertha Mason tears Jane's wedding veil on the eve of her marriage to Rochester; and, in the novel's most dramatic revelation, Rochester's marriage to Jane is halted at the altar when it is revealed that he already has a living wife — Bertha Mason, a Creole woman from Jamaica whom he married in his youth and who is now confined to the third storey of Thornfield, mad and dangerous. Rochester pleads with Jane to stay with him as his mistress, arguing that his marriage to Bertha was a sham forced upon him by his family for financial gain. Jane is deeply tempted — she loves Rochester passionately — but she refuses, insisting that she cannot sacrifice her self-respect and moral integrity. She flees Thornfield in the night, taking nothing with her.

The Thornfield section is the emotional and thematic heart of the novel. It explores the nature of love, the ethics of marriage, the tension between passion and principle, and the social constraints that govern women's lives. Rochester's secret — his imprisoned wife — raises profound questions about gender, power, and empire. Bertha Mason has been read as Jane's double, her "dark" self, a figure of female rage and confinement, and as a commentary on British colonialism in the Caribbean.`,
