        'Jane breaks the fourth wall with unusual intensity, addressing the reader directly as she describes the agony of leaving Rochester. The adjectives "stormy, scalding, heart-wrung" are characteristically Brontëan: they combine natural imagery (storm), physical sensation (scalding), and emotional violence (heart-wrung) into a single overwhelming experience. The appeal to the reader — "may you never feel" — is both protective and confessional: Jane wishes to spare the reader the pain she cannot spare herself. The passage demonstrates Brontë\'s commitment to emotional honesty: she does not minimise Jane\'s suffering or sentimentalise it, but presents it in its full, devastating reality.',
